Preparing Data for a Tableau Map

Alex Dragonetti

3-31-2024

1 Overview

We have been asked to create a Tableau Dashboard using the ‘Global Superstore’ dataset. The data is publicly available at https://github.com/pengdsci/sta553/raw/main/Tableau/GlobalSuperstore.xlsx

The data is a record of different sales and has information on the customer (name, location, etc), the product, shipping method, and profit.

We will use this data to construct a dashboard for quick visual analysis of sales and profit volumes. The goal is to find what practices and regions create the highest profit and sales volumes to allow for more informed decision making in the future. For example, if the company would like to increase profits in the future, this dashboard may help identify which regions focus on, shipping methods to incentivize, etc. Or, if the company would like to see which regions are lacking in sales, this may inform them. We will not make any specific recommendations from this dashboard, but will point out some key findings that it highlights.

2 Preparing the Data

There was no adjustment to the existing dataset, however, not all variables were used in the creation of the dashboard.

3 The Dashboard

Our dashboard has the following visualizations:

  • The global maps of sales volume and profit. This allows an individual to focus on a specific region and compare each country’s numbers. We would expect a higher sales volume to equal higher profits, but that is not always the case.
  • The graphs of sales and profit by region. Similar to above, we would expect proportional sizes of lines to indicate and equal share of sales and profit. This pair of graphs show which regions generate more profit per sale (and subsequently, which regions may be under-utilized or should be scaled back in). Notably, the regions of Canada, Central, and North show a disproportionately higher volume of profits while the regions of EMEA and Southeast Asia show disproportionately lower volume of profits.
  • The graphs of discount’s effect on sales and profit. This shows a point of diminishing returns seems to appear above a discount of 0.1 (10% off) globally, but one can check how the discount effects sales and profits in specific regions.
  • The graph of shipping mode vs profit and sales. This shows that the mode of shipping does not seem to effect profit on a sale. We would expect this to be the case if the cost of shipping is placed on the customer, so this is our confirmation. Barring new information, this shows that we should continue to offer our existing shipping options to customers and would not benefit significantly from incentivizing any particular method.

The dashboard can be seen on Tableau here:
